1
00:00:04,384 --> 00:00:30,054
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhudassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto sambha-sambhudassa

2
00:00:30,507 --> 00:00:35,213
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:38,256 --> 00:00:46,487
So this is a talk about eating meditation or using the process of eating for purposes of becoming fully liberated.

4
00:00:46,548 --> 00:00:49,932
So the first thing is, how bad can greed get?

5
00:00:51,905 --> 00:01:06,784
Eryxtheton, the Greek king of Thessaly, had a temerity to build a banqueting hall over the shrine of Demeter, goddess of earth's fertility and protector of the harvest.

6
00:01:08,105 --> 00:01:12,510
In Rome, she became Seres, from which we get the word, serial.

7
00:01:13,712 --> 00:01:16,254
She cursed him with insatiable hunger.

8
00:01:17,356 --> 00:01:21,641
First, he ate everything there was to eat in his kingdom.

9
00:01:22,093 --> 00:01:26,039
Then he started on his people and even ate his own family.

10
00:01:26,578 --> 00:01:29,042
Still famished, he ate himself.

11
00:01:31,084 --> 00:01:48,424
While I was staying at Khandaboda Meditation Centre in Sri Lanka, a man told me that once when out in the wilds he'd got lost and over a period of a few days became so hungry that when he finally caught a pigeon, he ripped it open and ate it raw.

12
00:01:49,266 --> 00:01:50,548
He was a good meditator.

13
00:01:51,980 --> 00:01:55,844
Hopefully we will not have to suffer such extreme conditions.

14
00:01:57,286 --> 00:02:02,152
Even so, there are other good reasons to investigate the process of eating.

15
00:02:03,052 --> 00:02:06,718
To distinguish between enjoying and indulging.

16
00:02:08,038 --> 00:02:14,407
To distinguish between the body and the mind, that is, sensations from emotions and thoughts.

17
00:02:15,729 --> 00:02:21,074
To distinguish between a desire and an action, the role of the will.

18
00:02:23,046 --> 00:02:27,495
So now, coming to distinguish between enjoying and indulging.

19
00:02:28,717 --> 00:02:35,991
We will want to make that distinction when we come to realise the suffering that indulgence causes.

20
00:02:37,894 --> 00:02:44,667
The first complication that arises from indulgence is attachment and compulsive behaviour.

21
00:02:45,557 --> 00:02:55,795
When we indulge some unwholesome but pleasing habit, it means that we are using something to create a certain mental state that we enjoy.

22
00:02:56,856 --> 00:03:02,867
It's not the biscuit we want, but the mental state it produces, be it happy or comforting.

23
00:03:03,949 --> 00:03:11,262
But this also produces a dependency, and just like any addict, we're compelled to raid the biscuit box.

24
00:03:12,658 --> 00:03:17,944
Only a strong act of will and refusal to have biscuits in the house can break the habit.

25
00:03:19,187 --> 00:03:26,634
It is precisely at the time we renounce the biscuit that we suffer the strength of that habit and the hold it has on us.

26
00:03:27,695 --> 00:03:29,818
But of course the potential is always there.

27
00:03:30,919 --> 00:03:41,231
Just as a person who gives up smoking and after a long time thinks they're immune to becoming habituated, on surrendering at a party to have just one,

28
00:03:41,616 --> 00:03:43,338
find themselves buying a packet.

29
00:03:44,540 --> 00:03:54,812
That is, attachment is none other than a dependency on something or indeed someone to create a mental state of happiness.

30
00:03:57,216 --> 00:04:02,143
The second complication is the suffering of frustration.

31
00:04:03,104 --> 00:04:10,492
Anger arises when we can't get what we want or what we want is denied us.

32
00:04:11,062 --> 00:04:14,989
We live at a time of almost immediate gratification.

33
00:04:15,949 --> 00:04:17,172
Consider fast food.

34
00:04:18,855 --> 00:04:27,668
Amazon has spent millions on delivery, knowing that to satisfy a customer as quickly as possible is to ensure their loyalty.

35
00:04:28,910 --> 00:04:29,992
You want some beer?

36
00:04:30,351 --> 00:04:31,653
Non-alcoholic, of course.

37
00:04:32,735 --> 00:04:34,117
We'll get it to you tomorrow.

38
00:04:35,413 --> 00:04:40,499
We can even be angry with ourselves for forgetting to buy tea or coffee.

39
00:04:41,019 --> 00:04:44,122
We get angry if the bus, the train, the taxi is late.

40
00:04:44,603 --> 00:04:47,165
We get angry if someone doesn't turn up for a meeting.

41
00:04:47,886 --> 00:04:50,127
Frustration doesn't help.

42
00:04:51,028 --> 00:04:51,928
It just burns us.

43
00:04:53,911 --> 00:04:55,432
The third is grief.

44
00:04:56,733 --> 00:04:59,115
The misery we feel when we have to diet.

45
00:04:59,156 --> 00:05:03,160
The shock we suffer when we lose a mobile.

46
00:05:04,033 --> 00:05:11,843
the distress of leaving an expensive hat or bag behind in a restaurant only to find it has disappeared.

47
00:05:12,944 --> 00:05:18,651
But although we believe in possessing things, in reality we can only use them.

48
00:05:20,113 --> 00:05:33,670
If a thief has run off with our mobile, for all intents and purposes it is their mobile, no matter how much we keep moaning and complaining of the loss of my mobile.

49
00:05:35,134 --> 00:05:41,983
And grief takes on a different intensity when we lose a spouse, partner, family member, friend.

50
00:05:44,165 --> 00:05:49,593
Fourthly, there's anxiety, which always sits beneath everything we possess.

51
00:05:51,035 --> 00:06:03,689
The run on flour, pasta and, bewilderingly, toilet paper at the start of the lockdown is driven by fear of what may or may not happen in the future.

52
00:06:05,172 --> 00:06:08,437
The more we possess, the more we feel loss.

53
00:06:09,720 --> 00:06:13,406
And the more we have to possess to cushion any blow.

54
00:06:14,307 --> 00:06:18,093
A billion pounds to a billionaire cannot be enough.

55
00:06:18,574 --> 00:06:21,218
They must cushion it by moving towards a trillion.

56
00:06:22,500 --> 00:06:28,951
We're afraid of loneliness, so we build up a coterie of friendships and lots of things to do.

57
00:06:29,927 --> 00:06:57,656
we feel insecure so we accumulate excessive insurance or power which manifests in controlling and bullying finally there is boredom now if you remember Mara the evil tempter the sensual life personified sent his three daughters to inveigle the Buddha to return to the good life sensual pleasure

58
00:06:58,125 --> 00:07:00,608
sexual pleasure and boredom.

59
00:07:01,689 --> 00:07:11,000
Boredom is that state where what once gave such pleasure and excitement is now stale, overindulged and unpleasing.

60
00:07:12,161 --> 00:07:17,369
It is an aversive state and to escape it we seek some other pleasure.

61
00:07:18,870 --> 00:07:24,656
Variety is the spice of life, is the basic motto of the consumerist.

62
00:07:26,105 --> 00:07:31,112
Consider the foodies who choose their holidays depending on a variety of restaurants.

63
00:07:32,514 --> 00:07:39,725
And just as all the other consequences of indulgence can become mental illness, boredom can drive you into depression.

64
00:07:40,206 --> 00:07:49,682
Indeed, what would be the purpose of living when there is nothing or anyone who can raise any degree of excitement?

65
00:07:51,822 --> 00:07:56,168
Here lies the distinction between happiness and excitement.

66
00:07:56,509 --> 00:08:00,514
True happiness is based on contentment.

67
00:08:00,535 --> 00:08:08,387
Excitement that passes for true happiness is based on an insatiable appetite for the new and the thrill.

68
00:08:09,968 --> 00:08:13,074
This excitement is what fuels consumerism.

69
00:08:14,074 --> 00:08:19,483
And the underlying engine is boredom, caused by the lack of excitement.

70
00:08:19,851 --> 00:08:25,160
that drives the consumer to seek relief in more excitement.

71
00:08:26,322 --> 00:08:29,026
This is none other than the psychology of addiction.

72
00:08:30,007 --> 00:08:47,073
Just as a drug addict feels normal when under the influence and abnormal when in need, so the consumer feels they have to buy something or go somewhere, do anything that excites, no matter how little, in order to feel happy.

73
00:08:48,100 --> 00:08:50,850
Retail therapy is no therapy at all.

74
00:08:51,532 --> 00:08:52,274
It's an addiction.

75
00:08:53,538 --> 00:09:00,202
The second noble truth states that the cause of suffering is the insatiable thirst

76
00:09:00,250 --> 00:09:19,980
which generates moment to moment becoming, accompanied by obsessive indulgence, finding fresh excitement now here, now there, namely, the insatiable hunger for sensual pleasures, for continued becoming and non-becoming.

77
00:09:22,677 --> 00:09:24,097
So, what do we do?

78
00:09:24,918 --> 00:09:42,437
Well, first of all, we need to make a clear distinction between the body and the mind, between, on the one hand, sensations and physical feelings, and on the other hand, the heart-mind, with its emotions and moods, thoughts and imagination.

79
00:09:42,456 --> 00:09:48,263
This is part of the endeavour to undermine the sense of self, the wrong view of self,

80
00:09:48,765 --> 00:09:58,495
This is the sense we have of being one entire undivided integer, a single uncompounded being, whole and absolute.

81
00:09:59,397 --> 00:10:16,596
By drawing apart what the body does through the senses and what the heart-mind does, is to begin to realize that we are but a compound made up of many pieces, all depending on each other, to create an embodied person.

82
00:10:18,735 --> 00:10:21,921
We are beginning to undermine this delusion.

83
00:10:22,481 --> 00:10:25,106
I am what I feel or think I am.

84
00:10:26,929 --> 00:10:30,836
Secondly, we need to distinguish a desire from an action.

85
00:10:32,078 --> 00:10:40,052
This will give us that chink of freedom where we can change the conditioning we don't want to a conditioning we do want.

86
00:10:41,230 --> 00:10:46,115
Remember, our personality is but a collection of habits and will always be so.

87
00:10:46,856 --> 00:10:56,488
Our work is to rid ourselves of habits that bring any degree of suffering and dissatisfaction and develop those that bring a sense of well-being.

88
00:10:58,350 --> 00:11:03,775
So long as there is only a desire, nothing has actually happened.

89
00:11:04,236 --> 00:11:08,942
It remains an idea laced with the energy of wanting.

90
00:11:09,142 --> 00:11:16,350
It arises out of a state of discomfort and is itself uncomfortable till gratified.

91
00:11:17,431 --> 00:11:32,787
If we are fully aware of a desire, we will not be caught up in its demands, but will have the occasion to ask whether it is wholesome, whether it's beneficial to myself, to another, or both myself and another.

92
00:11:33,374 --> 00:11:50,033
if we determine it is unwholesome all we have to do is bear with the desire until it burns itself out in so doing the habit that it expresses is weakened and will eventually lose all power over us

93
00:11:50,754 --> 00:11:54,519
If a desire is judged to be wholesome, well then we empower it.

94
00:11:55,120 --> 00:11:58,105
It produces an act of body, speech and mind.

95
00:11:58,865 --> 00:12:00,589
This reinforces the habit.

96
00:12:01,210 --> 00:12:04,033
In this quite simple way we can change ourselves.

97
00:12:04,354 --> 00:12:07,378
Though, as we discover, it's not easy.

98
00:12:08,239 --> 00:12:16,610
We need a highly alert attentiveness, or we are quickly gratifying those habits we don't want, and so developing them.

99
00:12:18,159 --> 00:12:23,388
In the Brahmuya Sutta, there's a passage describing how the Buddha receives food and eats it.

100
00:12:24,490 --> 00:12:27,153
Here, he's described what he actually experiences.

101
00:12:28,616 --> 00:12:34,787
He takes the food experiencing the taste, though not experiencing greed for the taste.

102
00:12:35,607 --> 00:12:38,552
In other words, just the pleasant sensations.

103
00:12:40,475 --> 00:12:44,522
This is on occasion chanted by monastics at mealtimes.

104
00:12:45,159 --> 00:12:48,563
Food, I take, has eight factors.

105
00:12:49,365 --> 00:13:08,264
It is neither for amusement or for intoxication, indulgence, or for the sake of physical beauty or attractiveness, but only for the endurance and continuance of my body, for ending discomfort and assisting the spiritual life.

106
00:13:08,683 --> 00:13:23,346
I consider, thus I shall terminate old unwholesome feelings without arousing new unwholesome feelings, and I shall be healthy and blameless and live in comfort.

107
00:13:25,408 --> 00:13:30,777
Now, what we're developing is an attitude, and an attitude is a way of relating.

108
00:13:32,019 --> 00:13:34,643
It's not specific to a particular object.

109
00:13:35,323 --> 00:13:38,168
So as we undermine greed around food,

110
00:13:38,552 --> 00:13:44,158
We're undermining all indulgence, for the same psychology appears to everything that delights us.

111
00:13:45,219 --> 00:13:53,407
Whether it's sensual pleasure, art, nature, even people and animals, the same problem of attachment arises.

112
00:13:54,629 --> 00:14:04,357
Once we've understood, I repeat, that attachment is a psychological dependency on some object or other for happiness,

113
00:14:05,148 --> 00:14:12,615
we begin to be more aware of other dependencies and slowly begin to let go of all obsessiveness.

114
00:14:14,596 --> 00:14:17,960
The Buddha tells us the taste of Nibbana is freedom.

115
00:14:18,700 --> 00:14:21,201
It's freedom from unwholesome desires.

116
00:14:23,124 --> 00:14:23,784
Now a warning.

117
00:14:24,566 --> 00:14:32,893
I once sat next to a monk, who by the look of him you would presume a true ascetic, hollow-cheeked and gaunt.

118
00:14:33,937 --> 00:14:43,707
When the delicious fruit salad with buffalo curd was offered, he placed it before him, and while the other monks continued to eat, he simply stared at the bowl.

119
00:14:44,649 --> 00:14:50,615
As we were finishing, he picked up the bowl and as quick as lightning spooned it down his throat.

120
00:14:51,995 --> 00:14:59,884
Now, of course, I may be judging him very wrongly, but it seemed to me that he was afraid of enjoying the food for fear of indulging.

121
00:15:01,166 --> 00:15:02,727
Such an attitude!

122
00:15:02,793 --> 00:15:08,321
if taken to all we enjoy, would turn life into a sour grape.

123
00:15:09,623 --> 00:15:18,517
As always, in our spiritual practice, we have to tread that narrow path between direct enemies and subtle enemies of virtues.

124
00:15:19,577 --> 00:15:32,057
Here, between indulgence and self-mortification, the pleasures and joys of life are a human birthright, but they come and go like everything else.

125
00:15:32,880 --> 00:15:35,303
what are we actually holding on to?

126
00:15:35,344 --> 00:15:49,942
In conclusion then, since our personality is made up of a compendium of habits, our psychotherapeutic task is to liberate ourselves from their control.

127
00:15:50,904 --> 00:15:53,567
But not the habit itself when it is wholesome.

128
00:15:54,149 --> 00:15:55,850
After all, we have to eat.

129
00:15:56,894 --> 00:16:07,424
So our task, when it concerns anything which is pleasurable and enjoyable, is to begin to experience what it is like to enjoy and not indulge.

130
00:16:09,006 --> 00:16:13,270
Our insight task is to see clearly how we create suffering.

131
00:16:14,292 --> 00:16:21,720
Suffer the renunciation of unskillful desires, arrive at unalloyed joy.

132
00:16:23,995 --> 00:16:37,346
i can only hope my words have been of some assistance that they have not caused confusion and that by your careful attentive eating you will liberate yourself from all suffering

